The {{nihongo|'''Satsumon culture'''|擦文文化|Satsumon Bunka}} is a post-[[Jōmon]], partially agricultural, archeological culture of northern [[Honshu]] and southern [[Hokkaido]] (700–1200 CE) that has been identified as the [[Emishi]], as a [[Japanese people|Japanese]]-Emishi mixed culture, as the incipient modern [[Ainu people|Ainu]], or with all three synonymously.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.be/books/about/Prehistoric_Japan.html?id=HpgcaKpnuU0C&redir_esc=y|title=Prehistoric Japan: New Perspectives on Insular East Asia|last=Imamura|first=Keiji|date=1996|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=|isbn=9780824818524|location=|pages=|language=en|quote=|ref=harv|via=}}</ref> It may have arisen as a merger of the [[Yayoi]]–[[Kofun period|Kofun]] and the [[Jōmon]] cultures. The Satsumon culture appears to have spread from northern Honshu into Hokkaido, [[Sakhalin]], the [[Kuril Islands]], and southern [[Kamchatka]], merging with or displacing the [[Okhotsk culture]] in those areas.{{sfn|Imamura|1996|p=204}}

